Ki Bin Kim -- Truist Securities -- Analyst

Yes. So just talking about the lease spreads, you guys mentioned that the spreads were pretty positive this quarter. I'm just curious about the net economic impact of the renewals or new leases. Meaning as you convert some of the percentage deals into fixed, is the net economic benefit you're getting as good as the comments made about spreads looking pretty positive?

David Simon -- Chairman, President, and Chief Executive Officer

Well, sure. I mean it's -- yes, because we obviously take into account our existing income stream from that space, which includes if we have overage or percent rent. And we're -- we look at it in totality, but we expect the total income stream to go up, and coding tends to be minimum rent increase and some assumption on overage. That's why rent spreads are kind of have whatever you want it to be.

OK? That's why we chose not to do it. So as an example, when we disclosed it historically, we included everything. We had minimum rent against minimum rent. We did not factor in overage.

Well, Taubman as an example, when they did their rent spreads, they included some assumption on overage. Well, when -- they disclosed it to their rent spreads. Is that beneficial or not beneficial? I mean the -- so to me, it's like, hey, it all shows up in cash flow, and so you see the cash flow, you see the NOI. So that's why you got to be very careful with rent spreads.

That's why they're more manufactured than they should be. They're -- in some cases, take assumptions and whether you want assumptions or not. We'd rather not have assumptions, so we just say here's the math. Minimum rent, you see our overage, you see the NOI, next question.

So -- but when we look at our -- when we go lease by lease, space by space, we're looking at the total income stream before and after the renewal, or in the case of a new tenant, to see whether we're going up or down or it's flat. And what I'm telling you is the trend is up, pretty straightforwardly.

Ki Bin Kim -- Truist Securities -- Analyst

OK. Great. And you guys mentioned that the lease percentage for your portfolio is about 200 basis points higher than that 94.5%. I'm just curious if you look at the forward leasing pipeline of new deals that you're looking at as we head into next year.

What does that picture look like compared to maybe a couple of quarters ago? And tied to that, I also noticed your 2023 lease expirations didn't really budge all that much quarter over quarter. Just any kind of preliminary thoughts on that role?

David Simon -- Chairman, President, and Chief Executive Officer

Yeah, there's good stuff out there. We're very close to it. Some of the larger accounts just takes time to do renewals, paper and all that stuff. So that's all moving, not real -- no real concerns there.

Go ahead, Brian.

Brian McDade -- Chief Financial Officer

And Ki Bin, you said about the 200 basis points. Let me just clarify. That is included within the current occupancy level. It is space -- it is leasing that has been done but hasn't commenced paying rent.

So that is next year -- effectively, will be partially next year's growth.

Ki Bin Kim -- Truist Securities -- Analyst

Thank you.

David Simon -- Chairman, President, and Chief Executive Officer

Thank you.

Operator

Thank you. Our last question is from Haendel St. Juste of Mizuho. Just go ahead.

Haendel St. Juste -- Mizuho Securities -- Analyst

Hey, there. Good morning.

David Simon -- Chairman, President, and Chief Executive Officer

Good morning.

Haendel St. Juste -- Mizuho Securities -- Analyst

I have a question, a follow-up for you on leasing. The occupancy is up 170 basis points year over year, but your lease income is only up about 60 basis points. My question is, when are we going to see the impact of that occupancy gain? Is that part of the cautious optimism embedded in your thinking for next year and your hopes for getting back to 2019 at levels? Or that'd be more of a full year '24 impact? Thanks.

David Simon -- Chairman, President, and Chief Executive Officer

Well, I think you've seen it, and you'll continue to see it. So our comp NOI growth the first nine months is...

Brian McDade -- Chief Financial Officer

4.4%.

David Simon -- Chairman, President, and Chief Executive Officer

4.4% So you've seen it for the first nine months, 4.4% growth. And then as Brian mentioned earlier and I have mentioned throughout the call is we had this other pipeline that's basically leases that will open and starting -- commencing rent in 2023. And that's why we're positive about the feeling that we'll continue to have future comp NOI growth for next year, even in the face of potential recessionary environment. OK?

Haendel St. Juste -- Mizuho Securities -- Analyst

Fair enough. And I guess as a follow-on to that. If we assume expenses have to go up given what's going on with inflation and operating expenses, personnel, is it your expectation that you can grow NOI between the fourth quarter year and middle of next year?

David Simon -- Chairman, President, and Chief Executive Officer

Absolutely. That's what I -- yes, we said we expect comp NOI growth next year. And obviously, that includes the expense side as well.

Haendel St. Juste -- Mizuho Securities -- Analyst

Right, right. I was thinking more than six months, but never mind. One more if I could squeeze in for Brian. Maybe it's a bit far off, but the $600 million unsecured maturing next June, bearing interest at 2 and 3 quarters, what's the early thinking there? And where do you think you could issue 10-year unsecured today?

Brian McDade -- Chief Financial Officer

Sure. Look, we actively monitor markets at all times, and you've seen us numerous times react ahead of maturities or at maturity, so we would expect to continue to keep our pulse on the finger of the market. Unsecured today is approximately 6% plus.

Haendel St. Juste -- Mizuho Securities -- Analyst

Great. Thank you.

David Simon -- Chairman, President, and Chief Executive Officer

All right. You sneaked in a few extra questions there. I think that was it on the question side. So thank you.

It's a change of pace in the morning, but we did it in hopes that you got home early not to trick or treat. And hopefully, you have a great Halloween. So thank you, and we'll talk to you soon.

Operator

[Operator signoff]

